<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-715-590  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 715 590.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  August 1 1990 v29 n15 p38(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Futurebus+ goes hard metric - and provokes hard questions.andO;(includes related article on the impact of profile changes)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Andrews, Warren.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Futurebus+ specification may have strict metric physicaldimensions by the time it receives IEEE approval.andP;  There isconcern that the specification may have to be changed in the nearfuture if the metric system is not adopted at the onset,especially with the formation of a united Europe in 1992 andmovement toward a metric standard internationally.andP;  The PhysicalLayer specification of the Futurebus+ is affected by proposedchanges.andP;  To date, only the A and B profiles have been defined,and discussions are under way for C and D profiles.andP;  Racks forFuturebus+ boards adhering to A and B are proposed for 300 mmheight and 300 mm depth.andP;  Final height would be 265 mm.andP;  Boarddepth would be 287.5 mm after provision is made for front paneland connector spacing on front and back.andP;  Spacing between boardsin a Futurebus+ rack has been set by the committee at 30 mm (1.2inches).andP;  Digital Equipment Corp is behind the shift to hardmetric standard and larger board dimensions.andP;  The move to largerboard size is advantageous to minicomputer and mainframemanufacturers because the larger board size provides space forimproved board functionality and less restriction for componentconfigurations.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (standards).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     IEEEStandardizationMetric SystemBusesSpecificationsFuturebus+.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Futurebus+ board dimensions. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>